Notes on the Trism Environment
------------------------------

(This doc typed on 30 Oct 1997)
(Last update: 7 Feb 1998)

A. TEnv.H

A.1. Redrawing

  A.1.1. Redrawing is generally initiated by the operating system.
  A.1.2. When a redraw handler is removed from the stack, the one
directly below is called to do a full redraw.
  A.1.3. Note that the converse isn't true: no special action is
undertaken at the moment a redraw handler is registered.

A.2. Enter/leave

  A.2.1. At the moment new mouse, motion and leave handlers are
registered, the old leave handler is called if the mouse was in the
window.
  A.2.2. A newly installed motion handler will be called immediately
to notify it of the current mouse position.
  A.2.3. When mouse, motion and leave handlers are deregistered, the
next highest motion handler will be called immediately to notify it of
the current mouse position.

A.3. Synchronised polling

  A.3.1. The THStack sync may be used to request calls at the moment
of a VSYNC event.
  A.3.2. Routines on this stack should return quickly.
  A.3.3. In XWindows, no VSYNC information is available. The sync
stack is therefore called just after the poll stack. Using the sync
stack instead of the poll stack may reduce flickering when porting to
other environments where VSYNC events are available.

A.4. Multithreading

  A.4.1. In theory, TEnv should be multithreaded. That is, it should be
OK to (de)register handlers from within such handlers. Multithreadedness
hasn't been tested very seriously though, so if you plan to do something
wild, check the source...

